<cvlonghorns@aol.com>

[In July 2008, the Netherlands (officially bovine tuberculosis-free
Member State), based on the epidemiological investigation followed by
the notification received from the United Kingdom, detected a number
of cases of infection with _Mycobacterium bovis_ in calves under 42
days of age coming from a single holding in the United Kingdom, that
went down with tuberculosis after the dispatch of the animals.

Dutch and Belgian farmers imposed a (self) ban on British cattle
following the revelation that 12 veal calves were positive for bovine
tuberculosis. The Dutch Agriculture Ministry condemned this breech of
biosecurity, particularly as there had been no TB in the Netherlands
since 1999; this was followed by discussions in Brussels, which led
to the publication of an acceptable regime for the interstate
(intra-EU) trade in bovines below 42 days of age. For the data on the
discussion and its outcome, see
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/report_working_group_bovine_tuberculosis.pdf>.

The results of investigations into the origin of the current case are
anticipated with interest. Is this a ramification/late emergence of
infection related to the 2008 event, or a new introduction into the
Netherlands? - Mod.AS]

[A map showing the location of Friesland in the north of the
Netherlands is available at
<http://www.mapsofworld.com/netherlands/maps/netherlands-map.jpg>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Netherlands can be
seen at <http://healthmap.org/r/03YH>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
